<subSubSection pageId="55" pageNumber="56" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="55.[189,324,265,291]" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[189,1398,313,375]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
The specific epithet is from the Latin ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2018" box="[630,741,313,339]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="clavigera">
<emphasis box="[630,741,313,339]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">clavigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, meaning ‘bearing claws’ and referring to the two clawlike lobes on the male superior lobe.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
